{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22280"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.1,0.28,0.03,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108115"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15245"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90525"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1710"},{"type":"tags","id":"2053"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40333"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108115"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is found unresponsive in a park early morning by a passerby. Empty pill bottles were found nearby. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with a Glasgow Coma Scale of 8. His pulse rate is 35/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 8/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and core temperature 28\u00b0C. His skin is cold and pale, with muscle rigidity noted. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals distant heart sounds and reduced air entry bilaterally. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the ECG abnormalities?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beta-blocker overdose","Hyperkalaemia","Tricyclic antidepressant toxicity","Hypocalcaemia","Hypothermia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe hypothermia (core temperature 28\u00b0C) after prolonged cold exposure. The ECG changes described are classic features of hypothermia and include bradycardia, prolonged PR and QT intervals, and the pathognomonic Osborn waves (J waves) - positive deflections at the end of the QRS complex. Shivering artefact may also be present on the ECG tracing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothermia\u003C/strong\u003E causes these characteristic ECG changes due to the direct effects of cold on cardiac conduction. The severity of ECG abnormalities typically correlates with the degree of hypothermia. Osborn waves become more prominent as core temperature drops below 32\u00b0C and are most evident in leads II, V5, and V6.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes peaked T waves, prolonged PR intervals, and widened QRS complexes, but does not produce Osborn waves. The profound hypothermia and characteristic ECG findings point to cold exposure as the primary cause rather than electrolyte disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETricyclic antidepressant toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E causes prolonged QRS and QT intervals with terminal R wave in aVR, right axis deviation, and may cause heart block. However, it does not produce Osborn waves. Despite the empty pill bottles found, the profound hypothermia and characteristic ECG findings point to cold exposure as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically causes QT prolongation but does not produce the bradycardia or Osborn waves seen in hypothermia. Cold exposure can secondarily affect calcium levels, but this would not be the primary cause of the ECG changes observed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-blocker overdose\u003C/strong\u003E can cause severe bradycardia and hypotension but does not produce Osborn waves or the constellation of ECG changes seen with hypothermia. The core temperature of 28\u00b0C and characteristic ECG findings strongly favour hypothermia as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hypothermia causes characteristic ECG changes including bradycardia, prolonged intervals, and Osborn waves (J waves).","Shivering artefact on ECG is a classic finding in conscious hypothermic patients but may be absent in severe cases.","ECG changes in hypothermia can mimic other conditions but the clinical context of exposure and core temperature are key diagnostic clues."],"references":["Life in the Fast Lane. Hypothermia - ECG Library [Internet]. Sydney: Life in the Fast Lane; [cited 2025 Jul 7]. Available from: https://litfl.com/hypothermia-ecg-library/","Mattu A, Brady WJ, Perron AD. Electrocardiographic manifestations of hypothermia. The American journal of emergency medicine. 2002 Jul 1;20(4):314-26."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90525"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21940"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21940"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZbTLexxSBtukADTKw9GRY15FkQIHZk.jpg","thumbUrl":"